explanation: To decide whether any executed operations inside OS_API_Init are "dead code" (i.e. their removal would not change program behaviour) the next analyzer must know: the global state layout and sentinel values, which control early-return and shutdown behavior (OS_SharedGlobalVars and its fields GlobalState, MicroSecPerTick, TicksPerSecond, DebugLevel; OS_INIT_MAGIC_NUMBER; OS_SHUTDOWN_MAGIC_NUMBER); the canonical success/error values used to gate progress (OS_SUCCESS, OS_ERROR); the object-type type and boundary that determine the for-loop range and which switch arms can execute (osal_objtype_t, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_USER and every OS_OBJECT_TYPE_* enumerator referenced in the switch); each initializer called by OS_API_Init whose return values and side-effects determine whether later code executes or must be undone (OS_ObjectIdInit, OS_API_Impl_Init and the implementation that can set time globals such as OS_Posix_TimeBaseAPI_Impl_Init, plus the per-type shared-layer inits and API_Init functions: OS_TaskAPI_Init, OS_QueueAPI_Init, OS_BinSemAPI_Init, OS_CountSemAPI_Init, OS_MutexAPI_Init, OS_ModuleAPI_Init, OS_TimeBaseAPI_Init, OS_TimerCbAPI_Init, OS_FileAPI_Init, OS_DirAPI_Init, OS_FileSysAPI_Init, OS_ConsoleAPI_Init, OS_CondVarAPI_Init, OS_NetworkAPI_Init, OS_SocketAPI_Init).  OS_ConsoleAPI_Init and its helpers (OS_ConsoleCreate_Impl, OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew, OS_ObjectIndexFromToken, OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken, OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew) are included because they may allocate resources (e.g. console task) whose creation affects whether restoring GlobalState to shutdown actually reverts behavior.  The OS_DEBUG macro and OSAL_CONFIG_DEBUG_PRINTF are required to determine whether debug/logging calls are compiled/executed (affecting whether those statements are semantics-bearing or truly removable).  Finally the UT_Stub_* test-stub symbols are listed because in test builds they can influence return values or side-effects observed during OS_API_Init; their presence can make certain branches reachable or change return_code, so they affect whether code is effectively dead.  Together these symbols let an analyzer determine which branches/operations can actually execute, whether they have externally observable side-effects (resource creation, global state changes, timing), and therefore whether removing them would alter program behaviour (i.e. whether they are dead code).
